Where and how new Russian citizens will pledge fealty to the Russian Federation, the president will determine such amendments to the second reading to the corresponding law developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Construction.
A week ago, the deputies planned to directly determine the order of taking oath in the law.
Children under 18 years of age and incapable will be released from the solemn oath, as well as incapable, follows from the amended text of amendments to the bill "On Citizenship of the Russian Federation" (there is at the disposal of "Izvestia"), which the committee will consider on July 11 before the second reading at its meeting.
President Vladimir Putin supported the idea of an oath when entering into Russian citizenship instead of formal signing of documents on June 6 during a meeting with State Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
The MPs issued this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading into a bill envisaging the abolition of the decision to extradite citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted for a number of terrorist or extremist crimes: for example, for public calls for terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (part). 2 Art. 205.2 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as for hijacking an aircraft, train or water transport, but only if this act is associated with terrorism (part). 4 st. 211 Criminal Code of the Russian Federation).
According to the bill, the logic was as follows: by drawing up documents for citizenship, a person signs under the promise to comply with the Russian legislation - getting on the path of extremism, he violates this promise.
In April, the bill was submitted to the Duma by Duma leaders Vladimir Vasiliev (United Russia), Gennady Zyuganov (CPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov (Just Russia) and Duma Speaker Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies accepted it in the first reading.
Last week the State Construction and Legislation Committee approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been revised again.
Now it says that the order of taking oath will be established by the president of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On Citizenship of the Russian Federation," indicating that the ceremony should be held in a solemn atmosphere in front of the state coat of arms and the flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - a list of places where the Russian coat of arms may be placed, was regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, offices of heads of state authorities of subjects, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could be the Registry Office.
Those who wish to obtain the citizenship of the Russian Federation will make a solemn oath after the officials check their documents.
But a Russian passport will be received only after taking an oath, follows from the modified text.
A week ago, the project said that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that Russia will be sworn from 18 years old, not from 14.
There is a rule by which incapable or limited capable, as well as those who cannot utter, read or personally sign the oath text will be released from taking an oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to release from this procedure and "other persons,"
Also, the updated bill outlines a special procedure for admission to Russian citizens of Ukrainian citizens, which are considered native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to officially renounce Ukrainian citizenship by granting for this a corresponding application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the statement will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
The refusal of "foreign" citizenship, as it is now, will not be required if it is stipulated by an international treaty or if it is impossible "due to persons-free reasons."
A group of deputies, including First Deputy Speaker of the Duma Ivan Melnikov (CPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrahov (all United Russia) proposed the corresponding amendment to the law.
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is not realistic, it is simply impossible.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for a decision on the citizenship of the Russian Federation, - explained the day before the head of the Duma committee on state construction and legislation Pavel Krasheninnikov (Yer).
In addition, the text clarifies that restrictions on the occupation of certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who in writing renounced "other" citizenship and handed over their previous passport to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but "for reasons beyond its control" it has not ceased to be a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are prohibited to occupy positions in the municipal service, to be hired to the facilities and in the organizations whose activities are related to ensuring the security of Russia.
Also, a person with double citizenship or a residence permit of another country cannot become a deputy of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law must come into force on September 1, 2017, by the time the necessary acts of law should be ready.
