Pre-expositional prevention (PrEP) is a course of HIV-positive drugs taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
According to studies, PREP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
When taking PrEP before sex in the human body, there are enough certain drugs to prevent infection with HIV.
Such drugs can be taken daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Patients entitled to receive the drug include homosexual and bisexual men, transgender and people whose partners are HIV-positive and do not receive successful treatment.
Dispensaries will select suitable participants who have agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgenders and persons whose partners are unknown whether their HIV status is restrained by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and attached to general practitioners in England will also be able to apply for potential participation in the nearest venereal clinic participating in the program.
