We faced this situation when there were in Misurata, and Haftar was on this day on board the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But they did not believe in Misrata in coincidence.
We were told, "You are probably very brave people who came to us today."
But our task is to show that we do not support Haftara alone, we are in dialogue with all key participants in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar communicated.
Does understanding with Russian partners at a human, emotional level make the fact that he studied twice in the USSR?
And, by the way, does Haftar know the Russian language?
He knows Russian if he knows, it is very relative.
But the fact that he studied with us, of course, facilitates dialogue with him.
And by the way, not only with him.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And here they speak Russian perfectly.
And to reach for Russia, to some extent they experience nostalgia on it.
Do you think it is a probable early abolition of the weapons embargo imposed against Libya?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
Of course, they are interested, but, as I said, we do not occupy someone else in this conflict and would not like to arm some at the expense of others.
We would like everyone to be in about equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, the Libyans constantly call for Russia to somehow contribute to its removal.
The process of constitution development is now actively advancing in Libya.
We hope that the parties will make compromise solutions, and reach an internal consensus.
Then the elections should be held, as discussed at the meeting of Saraj and Haftara.
If the elections take place and will finally be elected legitimate power (and now none of the parties has such a status), then it is possible to put in the UN Security Council the issue of lifting the weapon embargo.
To raise this question is now meaningless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees floating from Libya, feels abandoned by EU allies.
Can Moscow help Italian partners in this situation using their ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is the option that Haftara detachments will establish control over the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers who transport immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
Italians need support from Russia because Moscow is conducting a dialogue with both Haftar and Saraj, Misrata and the south of the country.
And in this issue, the tribes in southern Libya play a big role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it possible for Southers to stop the flows of migrants on distant approaches?
That is, conventionally speaking, the buses in which Nigerian migrants go back?
We are doing this.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in these streams to continue to go.
We hope to contribute to uniting the Southmen in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But to begin with, we would like to see the unity of the opinion on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The head of the government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of Sharia norms in the country.
How radical does he adhere to?
Will this become an obstacle in building relations with Russia or the West?
I will express my personal opinion about him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, the opponent of radical Islam.
But Islamists are in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
He is also actively fighting terrorists.
Where does he have such a reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli - it is the capital, there is legislative, executive and judicial power.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in not climbing there.
And we mixed them all the cards and began to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruck.
And we are already reaping the benefits of this work: Rosneft has concluded an agreement on cooperation with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
The director of NOC Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosneft Igor Sechin concluded the deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I believe that resell.
What other economic interests do Russia have in Libya?
The plans are to resign the contracts concluded under Muammar Gaddafi.
In particular, we are talking about the previous agreements in the transport sphere (building railways), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
And the Libyans have something to pay?
Well, they have oil.
That is, as in the case of Iran, we are talking about the scheme of "oil in exchange for services"?
I don't know what the scheme will be, I don't deal with these issues directly.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We are actually engaged in peacekeeping work there.
The main thing for us is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans agree with each other, so that they can establish order and Libya cease to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task - to help the Libyan people and squeeze out terrorists from there.
Do you have data on the presence of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR in Libya (now or earlier)?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to clarify this.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that today there is no one from Russia and other countries of the former USSR.
He said that he had about 50 thousand. Records of telephone conversations of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - "B") and Russian speech does not sound there.
And from which states then these militants?
I would not like to go into these details.
Then we will formulate the question differently.
How many Islamic militants in Libya themselves are many of the Islamic militants themselves?
There are practically no Libyans among them, they are not more than 5%.
The rest are the migrants.
