Michel Carter's verdict for reports that led to the suicide of Conrad Roy
A Massachusetts resident was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for leading to suicide by her boyfriend Conrad Roy with the help of text messages and phone calls.
Michel Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months of his term in the grid and another 5 years of probation period.
Carter was found guilty of the unintentional murder of Conrad Roy in June, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at the hearings on Thursday: "My family is killed by grief.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to remain free before the appeal.
She was threatened with a maximum term of 20 years, but her lawyers said that she and Roy suffered mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing, clinging her hands and bowing her eyes.
"With her actions she killed Konrad Roy," the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve her.
She did not recognize the responsibility," she said.
"She did not show repentance."
But the lawyer Carter said it was a "tragic case she is deeply sorry for."
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that, in his opinion, her "age, the level of maturity, or even mental illness did not affect her actions noticeably."
The defendant read the statements of Roy Lynn Roy's mother, saying: "No day has passed when I would not mourn for the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I cope - I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever," he says.
Roja Kamdin Roy said that she was invigorating to the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become aunt of his children.
"To be a person who has always been with me since my birth is a pain that will remain with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case seems to be a legal precedent, as Massachusetts does not have a law that would provide for the responsibility for the advice of a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case attracted the attention of the whole country, when it became known that it was pushed to suicide Carter's message.
"You can hang up, jump from the roof, I don't know how to kill yourself with a knife," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before the suicide, she wrote, "You have to do it, Conrad" and "You only have to turn on the ignition, and you will be free and happy."
Judge Monis said that Carter wanted to get attention with the help of Roy's death, and forbade her to communicate with the press to prevent her from getting the desired.
The opinions of the lawyers on this issue are divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 for the murder in Italy of his British neighbor in the apartment and justified two years later.
30-year-old Knox published in Los Angeles Times her special opinion, which stated: "Michel Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
