But 700 years from his cozy place in the valley of the river Beul in the county of Kent, he watched the turbulent history around, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, Yorkshire with a spear hair and with a tendency to historical documents, a novel comic.
"I think it's so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago," he says with enthusiasm.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand."
The "lock in England" covers a period from the Middle Ages to the Eidian era and tells about the families that lived in Skotney; each story illustrated one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkevic, Bryoni May Smith, William Exley, Bekki Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This is not the first Rhodes book, which is based on archival data: in 2014 he wrote "The Thick Bowls of a Dead Man and Other Stories" - a collection of documents from the British Library; this project unexpectedly touched him to the bottom of his heart.
"I could only be stirred by the fingerprint on the edge of the letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for Yakobits," he says.
"It's his fingerprint"
And the letters are always smelled of smoke, for in those days the fire was kindled for the light.
And in 300 years, in the future, it seems to you that you are also there.
Ah, how I love the archives!"
For a man covered by such a passion for old papers, to get support from the National Fund and the English Art Studies Council and to live in the castle for four months ("Honestly, I have a little gone there") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes studied the "new" Victorian castle for days, walked through the archives and considered numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, the heads of hyen on the walls or bottles that have been in the drows for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talked to the foresters, gardeners and sometimes with artists who worked on illustrations to his book.
Then at night he "drinked whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of Skotney Castle is not very studied because the National Fund got full access to it only in 2006, when the last heir died, Elisabeth Hassi.
When Rhodes arrived there in ten years, the staff just began to deal with the archive, which he describes as "that the aristocrats for centuries fell into the attic."
The diaries, the letters of the times of the British Empire, the maps showing who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring," says Rhodes, "but here two families fought for this birch.
It happens so, guys!"
In some stories of the collection, the castle becomes a starting point for wider research in English history: for example, in the "Worker," the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
"There is information about the revolt that took place in the castle in 1380, in a book called "The Knight's Families of Kent and Sussex," says Rhodes.
"The cross-country uprising began in these places, and I thought that revolt was a suitable beginning.
Maybe they were tied up?"
Other subjects are closely related to the history of the castle - for example, the "Life," which tells about the priest-Jesuit, which the Darrelov family hid seven years during the English Reformation.
Or the "Contrabandist," about the 18th century smuggler Arthur Darrel, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by typing the coffin with stones (it was discovered a few years later, when the coffin was dug up).
Darrels are the favorite Rhodes family of all that Scotty inhabited: "Gentlemen seem to have been a perfect swindler, always went into debt and spent money on what they could not afford.
In different generations, the Darrel men solved their problems with their debts, marrying wealthy elderly women - I imagine them as a company of cute guys who know how to care for the heirs of great fortunes."
After finishing work in the castle Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to get a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elyamenmyaki - a place where in the early 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it was overgrown with forest again.
But Skotney remains a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
"I felt like this: the devil, I have to return to real life again."
Fifteen largest banks choose "Russia"
The conflict in the Association of Russian Banks (ARB) is developing: following Sberbank, VTB, VTB-24, Alpha-bank, Gazprombank, Rosselkhozbank, Binbank and FC Open, seven more credit organizations are going to leave this public organization.
Thus, the organizations that came out of the ARB will account for at least 80 percent of the market.
But this is not just a way out - all the banks that have declared a break with the ARB are negotiating with another public organization uniting credit institutions - the Association of Regional Banks "Russia," which is headed by well-known politician Anatoly Aksakov, chairman of the State Duma Committee on Financial Markets, recognized, by the way, following the results of the last session and the most effective head of the Duma committee and deputy on the number of drafted bills.
The beginning of the conflict within the ARB was laid during the discussion in the Federation Council, when the Interregional Banking Council considered new bills, in particular, involving a new classification of banks depending on the size of the authorized capital.
Then Garegin Tosunyan, President of the ARB, said that, according to the association, this bill is adopted in the interests of the largest banks, which thus try to limit the possibilities of small and medium-sized banks in the regions, intercepting their clientele.
Among other claims, there was also criticism of the Central Bank, which, according to Tosunyan, does not always justify itself with the revocation of licenses from some banks, which, however, was objected by the representative of the Central Bank: many leaders of the bank, in particular, Vneshprombank, were members of the governing bodies of the ARB.
Apparently, this exchange of mutually exclusive opinions in a very sensitive attitude to the relations with the main regulator of the banking environment and became a visible reason for the fifteen largest banks, having disagreed with the ARB policy, began to prepare for joining the association "Russia," noting that "the effectiveness of the work of the ARB is hollowing at a low level, and constructive dialogue within the banking community is not actually carried out."
Depositors will be better
What will end the matter?
We will immediately answer the main question that arises at the slightest failure or conflict in the banking sector or next to it: the depositors do not threaten anything, on the contrary, the reliability of the banking system will increase.
Anatoly Aksakov, head of "Russia," is known for his scrupulousness in all that concerns the interests of banks and their clients, a high-level professional, who is highly appreciated in the Central Bank: almost all the management of the Central Bank is present at the annual activities of the association, and all significant legislative initiatives of the regulator pass through expert assessments of "regionals."
Apparently, there is no significant upheavals in the personnel-organizational plan.
Undoubtedly, the ARB falls into a difficult financial and management situation after it loses such powerful and influential participants with their contributions and lobbying capabilities.
However, in this oldest - established in 1991 - an organization that defends the interests of the banking community, there is considerable potential to continue to improve banking legislation and the sphere of monetary circulation as a whole.
It is impossible to say that in the association "Russia" with open arms, they are ready to accept new members on any terms, judging by the reaction of its head, Anatoly Aksakov ("maybe want too much to want"), who on July 21 at a briefing in the press center of the Parliamentary newspaper, said that "literally the next day representatives of the ARB banks who left the ARB asked me to consider the possibility to increase the potential of our association "Russia."
Their proposals are to strengthen the voice of bankers in the Association Council, as well as to pay more attention to new banking technologies.
Now the negotiation process is underway, proposals of both sides are being studied, the agenda of the extraordinary congress of the association is being prepared, which will be held in Sochi in mid-September within the framework of the international banking forum.
There and let's decide.
Anatoly Aksakov also stressed that "he does not stay for the chair," called Georgy Luntovsky, the new head of the renewed Russia Association, who leaves the post of Deputy Chairman of the Central Bank in September, highly characterizing his business and human qualities.
On August 18, Anatoly Aksakov, who is now resting in the Crimea, plans to stop vacation for one day and arrive in Moscow, at an extraordinary meeting of the Association Council "Russia," where it is planned to consider the agenda of the extraordinary congress "Russia."
