Red meat, dairy products and chocolate can help facilitate the HDC.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies talk about the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help relieve symptoms in those who suffer from inflammatory bowel diseases.
This is an incurable disease that suffers from approximately 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colics and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to mitigate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from Washington University have found that the main amino acid of the protein triptophan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase the colon tolerance.
Leading researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the intestines ensure that harmful microbes coming with food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of starting an inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body and thus harming sensitive tissues.
If the equilibrium is too severely disturbed towards inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice with a certain bacteria in the intestines appear increasing the tolerance of the cells.
And this bacteria need triptophan - one of the building elements of the protein - to start the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a connection between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of the normal intestinal microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more triptophane contained in the nutrition of mice, the more of these immune cells they had."
He assumed that the same will work for people: the combination of L. reuteri and the rich triptophane diet can contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation of the environment in the intestines.
Dr. Louisa Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying the variety of increasing the tolerance of immune cells, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, and another group, which belonged to the same line, but was kept separately, they were not.
She suggested that the difference can be caused by mice intestinal microbioms - communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi, which usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the intestine cells of mice was sequenced, and six species of bacteria present in mice, having immune cells, but missing in mice that do not have them, were found.
Mice grown in a sterile environment, which did not have a good microbiom and did not develop this kind of immune cells, received L. reuteri, and their immune cells appeared.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of liquid - without bacteria - to the undeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have become cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the trimtona refining, known as indol-3-milk acid.
When researchers doubled the number of triptophanes in mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of triptophane was halved, the number of cells also fell twice.
Dr. Cervantes Barragan explains that people have the same increasing cell tolerance as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in its gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether triptophanes from L. reuteri contribute to the development of cells in humans as well as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases, defects in genes associated with triptophane were found.
She says: "Perhaps the development of these cells we need to strengthen, because the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of triptophane in the presence of L. reuteri can potentially lead to expansion of their population."
