The White House's requisite has cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to the records of the armed forces provided to the journal, the White House's decision last month to bring the helicopter of the marines to the South Lawn for the event dedicated to the American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as 24,000 dollars.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the Marine One, when the president is on board, became the central element of the event held on July 17 in the White House, which was demonstrated by American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pens and the top officials of the White House inspected technological products from all fifty states.
The helicopter, produced in Connecticut, was exhibited near the yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Helicopter Squadron of Marines (HMX-1), the Helicopter Division, the White House Military Administration ordered the presence of a helicopter in a private order, or FRAGO, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an unusual event.
"I just wanted you to make sure that you are aware of, because it is an unusual widely covered event in the press," wrote the commander of HMX-1 in an e-mail to his chief, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter stated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at about 7 am on July 17 to participate in the event scheduled for 3 o'clock in the day, and will remain there before the lawn is released between 6 and 9 pm on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the restrictions on the hours of work.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the security staff of the unit remained near the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was unclear from the records received by the journal that it was not clear whether the second crew was required in the end.
The Hatch law prohibits federal officials from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 specified whether the event is not contrary to this decision.
"At other hand, we asked if this is a violation of the Hatch law, and we were told that no," the commander wrote.
"It seems that you have nowhere to go," answered the deputy chief.
The event "Made in America" was announced by the White House as an official event, and the Hatch law was not applied to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made an effort to promote the health reform, which was then in the development of the Senate, and praised the attempts to regulate government decisions.
The use of aircraft known as the Marine One and the Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are instructed to use them for travel.
But it is unusual to request them only in the interests of photo-possibilities.
Trump has already become a subject of discussion in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during his first electoral rally in Melbourne, in the state of Florida, and his Twitter account is blocked with reports of complaints about the use of the presidential aircraft by his predecessor.
"The White House is delighted with the show "Made in America," which presented products from 50 states, made by American workers from American materials," said Deputy Press Secretary of the White House Lindsey Walters.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington agglomeration and the South Lawn to train the transport of the President of the United States to the White House with an accuracy of inches.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 held 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight, carried out for the event "Made in America," was counted on the crew at the expense of the necessary training flights in a month.
The helicopters of the unit also flew 11 additional hours on that day within the framework of the "Ne-presidential tasks for the provision of support."
According to the White House, taxpayers did not have the costs for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
The representative of the company "Sikorsky" said that the company did not take part in the organization of a demonstration of a helicopter in the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not take into account the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the hourly rates of the Ministry of Defense for 2017 fiscal year, the rate of compensation of the Ministry of Defense for VH-3D is 24,380 USD per hour of flight.
The department recorded that the airtime was 30 minutes each side of its airborne base on the Kuantiko aviation base in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this rate.
"To calculate the value for taxpayers, based on the approximate rate of compensation, is completely wrong," says Walters.
"These exemplary rates include the personnel, service and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual appropriations.
According to a study conducted in 2015 by the corporation RES, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of the personnel, but, indeed, take into account the cost of fuel, service and costs specified in the contract.
At that time, the former spokesman of the White House, Sean Speyser, spoke in defense of the use of a helicopter for the event.
"The idea is to demonstrate this week the things done in America," said Speyser.
I know that the company "Sikorsky" and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose workplace depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment, the creation of which so many Americans worked tirelessly.
Therefore, of course, it is absolutely appropriate to pay attention to this.
It was not clear whether Trump interacted with a helicopter, inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he definitely sat on a driver's seat in a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed the representatives of the company "Sikorsky" joked with the press on the topic of his own fleet of products of the company.
"I know very well about Sikorsky," said the president. I have three of them.
