The senior organizer of Dru Duffy said: "The members of our trade union are deeply concerned that we cannot make it clear from the general head of the facility on business needs and the investment plan for the future of Tolkrossa.
Families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is large in the local society and in the territory of the Great Glasgow; it is the most important pillar of decent work in the territory of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Thus, in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the background of Brexit, the growth of the subsistence minimum and chronic decline in production, East End Glasgow desperately needs the prosperity of production at the McVitie's factory.
According to the representative of Pladis, the head of the Shostros object only yesterday received a letter from the Scottish branch of GMB, and the company will respond immediately, as we appreciate our constant cooperation with the employees and representatives of the trade union.
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting with GMB employees and representatives in Tolkros, where we openly discussed a number of issues.
We talked to the staff that, like all companies operating under the most competitive and unstable economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our actions, and this concerns all our facilities and activities to remain competitive.
"In recent years, we have invested more than 5 million pounds in our Slushrosk facility, especially in production lines and improvement of functional indicators.
We are fully aware of the value of Tolkros as a production facility, and in case of any changes in the work on this facility, the employees and representatives of the trade union will learn about it first.
